./sdp/verification/t-010@20260408t223256za-verify.md:16:1. `cypherclaw_daemon.ollama_health()` returns a JSON-serializable summary for both sockets (`11434`, `11435`). The test asserts `json.loads(json.dumps(result)) == result` and passes.
./sdp/verification/t-010@20260408t223256za-verify.md:17:2. Each per-socket summary includes `socket`, `port`, `healthy`, `status`, `models`, and `latency_ms`, matching the spec's required schema exactly.
./sdp/verification/t-010@20260408t223256za-verify.md:18:3. Single-socket and dual-socket probe failures degrade gracefully: failed instances return `healthy: False`, `models: []`, `latency_ms: null` without raising.
./sdp/verification/t-010@20260408t223256za-verify.md:20:The `ollama_probe` delegation is correct — `check_health` and `check_models` are called only in the appropriate conditions.
./sdp/verification/t-010@20260408t223256za-verify.md:25:- Both sockets healthy → verified
./sdp/verification/t-010@20260408t223256za-verify.md:28:- `check_models` not called when unhealthy → verified (the dual-unhealthy test uses `pytest.fail` as the stub)
./sdp/verification/t-010@20260408t223256za-verify.md:30:One edge case from the spec ("instance responds but has no loaded models, still marked healthy with empty `models` list") is not explicitly tested. However, `check_models` in `ollama_health.py` is guaranteed to return `[]` when the `/api/ps` payload has no `models` key or an empty list, and the daemon passes this through without filtering. The behavior is correct but untested.
./sdp/verification/t-010@20260408t223256za-verify.md:32:The latency timer wraps only `check_health`, not the subsequent `check_models` call — consistent with the spec's phrasing "wall-clock timer around the health probe."
./sdp/verification/t-010@20260408t223256za-verify.md:36:- Pattern of importing an existing module as a namespaced alias (`import ollama_health as ollama_probe`) matches how similar helpers are imported in the daemon.
./sdp/verification/t-010@20260408t223256za-verify.md:39:- `_ollama_instance_health` follows the private-helper + public-function pattern used throughout the daemon.
./sdp/verification/t-010@20260408t223256za-verify.md:44:No security concerns. All HTTP probes target `localhost` only (ports 11434/11435). No secrets are handled. `check_health` and `check_models` both catch network errors internally and return safe defaults, so no exception paths leak connection details.
./sdp/verification/t-010@20260408t223256za-verify.md:49:- All 3 target tests in `tests/test_ollama_daemon_health.py` pass cleanly in 0.12s.
./sdp/verification/t-010@20260408t223256za-verify.md:51:- One minor inefficiency: each healthy instance makes two sequential HTTP requests to `/api/ps` (once for `check_health`, once for `check_models`). This is because both functions independently call `_read_ps`. The latency reported only covers the first call. This is not a blocking issue given the synchronous, side-effect-free design requirement, but could be improved in a follow-up.
./sdp/verification/t-010@20260408t223256za-verify.md:56:- [ ] Double `_read_ps` call per healthy instance (check_health + check_models both call the endpoint) — severity: minor (performance, not correctness)
./sdp/verification/t-010@20260408t223256za-verify.md:64:1. Add a test for the case where `check_health` returns True but `check_models` returns `[]` (e.g., Ollama is up but no models are loaded). The production code handles it correctly; a test makes the guarantee explicit.
./sdp/verification/t-010@20260408t223256za-verify.md:65:2. Consider a future refactor of `_ollama_instance_health` to call `_read_ps` once and derive both `healthy` and `models` from the same response — would halve the HTTP traffic per probe and give a more accurate total round-trip latency. Out of scope for this subtask.
